1
00:03:09,607 --> 00:03:13,194
[door opens, shuts]

2
00:03:51,232 --> 00:03:53,234
[shivers]

3
00:03:58,739 --> 00:04:01,617
[jazz music]

4
00:04:01,659 --> 00:04:04,828
[door opens, shuts]

5
00:04:09,416 --> 00:04:11,919
- It's getting cold.
- Thanks.

6
00:04:15,589 --> 00:04:17,758
That is one fine frame.

7
00:04:18,842 --> 00:04:20,886
One fine frame, that is.

8
00:04:20,970 --> 00:04:22,680
[shivers]

9
00:04:22,763 --> 00:04:24,598
How much...

10
00:04:26,475 --> 00:04:30,813
...does a fine frame
like that cost, do you think?

11
00:04:31,981 --> 00:04:33,732
I never told you,

12
00:04:33,816 --> 00:04:36,944
but you sound a little like
Dr Seuss when you're drunk.

13
00:04:37,027 --> 00:04:39,029
Anna, I'm serious.

14
00:04:40,197 --> 00:04:42,199
Serious, I am, Anna.

15
00:04:44,493 --> 00:04:47,329
I'd say it cost
at least a couple hundred.

16
00:04:47,371 --> 00:04:49,748
I'm gonna read it for you.

17
00:04:49,832 --> 00:04:51,583
Do I really sound like Dr Seuss?

18
00:04:51,667 --> 00:04:54,712
"In recognition of his
outstanding achievement

19
00:04:54,753 --> 00:04:57,131
in the field of child psychology,

20
00:04:57,214 --> 00:04:59,216
his dedication to his work

21
00:04:59,258 --> 00:05:02,845
and his continuing efforts
to improve the quality of life..."

22
00:05:02,886 --> 00:05:05,889
Will you concentrate?

23
00:05:05,973 --> 00:05:09,393
"...his continuing efforts
to improve the quality of life

24
00:05:09,476 --> 00:05:12,688
for countless children
and their families,

25
00:05:12,730 --> 00:05:16,442
the city of Philadelphia
proudly bestows upon its son,

26
00:05:16,525 --> 00:05:19,153
Dr Malcolm Crowe..." That's you.

27
00:05:19,236 --> 00:05:22,656
"...the Mayor's Citation
for Professional Excellence."

28
00:05:24,241 --> 00:05:27,244
They called you their son.

29
00:05:27,286 --> 00:05:29,747
Wow.

30
00:05:29,788 --> 00:05:32,458
We should hang it in the bathroom.

31
00:05:35,586 --> 00:05:38,213
This is an important night for us.

32
00:05:39,757 --> 00:05:44,094
Finally, someone is recognising
the sacrifices you've made.

33
00:05:44,136 --> 00:05:48,223
That you have put everything
second, including me...

34
00:05:48,265 --> 00:05:51,769
...for those families
that they're talking about.

35
00:05:55,606 --> 00:05:58,942
They're also saying
that my husband has a gift.

36
00:06:00,235 --> 00:06:03,822
You have a gift that teaches
children how to be strong

37
00:06:03,906 --> 00:06:08,619
in situations where most adults
would piss on themselves.

38
00:06:08,702 --> 00:06:11,538
I believe what they wrote is real.

39
00:06:15,667 --> 00:06:17,503
Thank you.

40
00:06:21,382 --> 00:06:24,009
[Malcolm] I would like
some wine in a glass.

41
00:06:24,093 --> 00:06:28,180
I would not like it in a mug.
I would not like it in a jug.

42
00:06:28,263 --> 00:06:31,100
[giggling]

43
00:06:39,483 --> 00:06:42,194
[grunting]

44
00:06:53,122 --> 00:06:55,040
Look.

45
00:06:57,501 --> 00:06:59,503
[phone beeping]

46
00:07:07,636 --> 00:07:08,804
[screams]

47
00:07:37,875 --> 00:07:40,836
Anna, don't move.
Don't make a sound.

48
00:07:45,215 --> 00:07:47,384
This is 47 Locust Street.

49
00:07:49,011 --> 00:07:52,181
You've broken a window
and entered a private residence.

50
00:07:52,222 --> 00:07:54,391
You don't know so many things.

51
00:07:56,059 --> 00:07:57,561
There are no needles

52
00:07:57,644 --> 00:08:00,314
or prescription drugs
of any kind in this house.

53
00:08:01,899 --> 00:08:03,734
[gasps]

54
00:08:05,819 --> 00:08:07,988
[sobbing]

55
00:08:09,865 --> 00:08:12,868
Do you know why you're
afraid when you're alone?

56
00:08:15,329 --> 00:08:17,998
I do. I do.

57
00:08:18,999 --> 00:08:21,251
What do you want?

58
00:08:21,335 --> 00:08:23,045
What he promised me!

59
00:08:23,086 --> 00:08:26,548
- I want what he promised me.
- Oh, my God.

60
00:08:26,590 --> 00:08:27,591
Do I know you?

61
00:08:27,674 --> 00:08:30,010
Don't you know me, hero?

62
00:08:31,094 --> 00:08:33,514
Don't you even remember
your own patients?

63
00:08:35,015 --> 00:08:36,767
[sobbing continues]

64
00:08:36,850 --> 00:08:39,686
D... downtown clinic.

65
00:08:39,770 --> 00:08:42,689
S... single-parent family.

66
00:08:44,650 --> 00:08:46,568
Possible mood disorder.

67
00:08:48,362 --> 00:08:50,822
I was afraid!

68
00:08:50,906 --> 00:08:54,701
You told me I was having trouble
coping with my parents' divorce.

69
00:08:54,785 --> 00:08:58,664
You... you were wrong.
You were wrong.

70
00:08:58,747 --> 00:09:01,208
[sobbing]

71
00:09:01,291 --> 00:09:03,835
Now look at me!

72
00:09:03,919 --> 00:09:06,129
I don't want to be afraid no more.

73
00:09:06,213 --> 00:09:08,382
Please, just give me a minute to think.

74
00:09:08,465 --> 00:09:10,968
I waited ten years for you!

75
00:09:11,051 --> 00:09:13,637
I'm not giving you nothing!

76
00:09:13,720 --> 00:09:15,472
Ben Friedkin?

77
00:09:15,556 --> 00:09:18,892
Some people, they call me "freak".

78
00:09:19,935 --> 00:09:22,104
Ronald Sumner?

79
00:09:22,145 --> 00:09:25,315
I am. I am a freak. Look at...

80
00:09:26,525 --> 00:09:28,360
Vincent.

81
00:09:29,528 --> 00:09:31,530
Vincent Grey.

82
00:09:34,575 --> 00:09:36,451
Don't. Don't.

83
00:09:36,493 --> 00:09:38,954
I do remember you.

84
00:09:38,996 --> 00:09:41,999
- No.
- Quiet, very smart.

85
00:09:43,333 --> 00:09:45,919
Compassionate.

86
00:09:46,003 --> 00:09:48,839
Unusually compassionate.

87
00:09:50,674 --> 00:09:52,676
You forgot "cursed".

88
00:09:55,929 --> 00:09:58,599
You failed me.

89
00:09:58,682 --> 00:10:01,018
You failed me!

90
00:10:04,354 --> 00:10:08,442
Vincent, I'm sorry if I
wasn't... if I didn't help you.

91
00:10:08,525 --> 00:10:11,361
But if you just... let me try.

92
00:10:11,445 --> 00:10:13,614
You just give me a chance...

93
00:10:13,697 --> 00:10:15,949
- [groaning]
- [Anna screams]

94
00:10:18,493 --> 00:10:20,162
[gunshot]

95
00:10:21,580 --> 00:10:24,416
- Oh, God. Oh, God, honey.
- [groaning]

96
00:10:24,499 --> 00:10:27,127
- Did Vincent...
- Now, don't talk. Shh.

97
00:10:27,210 --> 00:10:29,212
[groaning]

98
00:12:44,931 --> 00:12:48,101
[boy] <i>De profundis clamo ad te, Domine.</i>

99
00:12:49,811 --> 00:12:53,315
<i>De profundis clamo ad te, Domine.</i>

100
00:12:57,819 --> 00:13:00,113
It's OK, Cole.

101
00:13:00,197 --> 00:13:03,658
My name is Dr Malcolm Crowe.

102
00:13:03,700 --> 00:13:07,704
We were supposed to meet today,
but I missed our appointment.

103
00:13:07,788 --> 00:13:09,623
I'm sorry.

104
00:13:18,215 --> 00:13:20,759
You know,
in the olden days in Europe,

105
00:13:20,842 --> 00:13:22,886
people used to hide out in churches.

106
00:13:22,969 --> 00:13:25,806
They would claim sanctuary.

107
00:13:30,685 --> 00:13:32,854
What were they hiding from?

108
00:13:36,107 --> 00:13:38,485
Bad people, mostly.

109
00:13:38,568 --> 00:13:43,323
People that wanted to put
them in jail... hurt them.

110
00:13:45,408 --> 00:13:49,579
Noticed your eyeglasses. They
don't have any lenses in them.

111
00:13:49,663 --> 00:13:51,832
They're my dad's.

112
00:13:51,915 --> 00:13:54,376
The lenses hurt my eyes.

113
00:13:54,417 --> 00:13:57,420
What were you talking
about with your soldiers

114
00:13:57,504 --> 00:13:59,381
when I came in?

115
00:13:59,422 --> 00:14:04,302
<i>- De...
- De profundis clamo ad te, Domine.</i>

116
00:14:04,386 --> 00:14:06,388
It's called "Latin".

117
00:14:10,350 --> 00:14:12,602
All your soldiers speak Latin?

118
00:14:12,686 --> 00:14:14,354
No.

119
00:14:14,437 --> 00:14:16,273
Just one.

120
00:14:18,400 --> 00:14:21,278
Are you a good doctor?

121
00:14:21,361 --> 00:14:23,196
Well...

122
00:14:24,281 --> 00:14:27,284
I used to be.

123
00:14:27,367 --> 00:14:31,621
I won an award once
from the mayor.

124
00:14:31,663 --> 00:14:33,999
Had an expensive frame.

125
00:14:47,846 --> 00:14:50,348
I'm gonna see you again, right?

126
00:14:50,432 --> 00:14:53,184
If that's OK with you.

127
00:15:04,613 --> 00:15:09,034
[door opens, shuts]

128
00:15:27,177 --> 00:15:28,345
It's me.

129
00:17:04,274 --> 00:17:06,276
[bell tolling]

130
00:17:10,155 --> 00:17:12,699
[helicopter blades whirring]

131
00:17:15,702 --> 00:17:18,788
<i>[radio] Pennsylvania Turnpike
westbound slow to Valley Forge 24.</i>

132
00:17:18,872 --> 00:17:22,834
<i>On the Blue Ridge both directions,
generally slow between number three...</i>

133
00:17:24,961 --> 00:17:27,881
- [dog barks]
- Hey, good morning.

134
00:17:35,472 --> 00:17:37,307
Cole?

135
00:17:40,810 --> 00:17:42,645
Cole?

136
00:17:43,813 --> 00:17:46,483
Hey, your Cocoa Puffs
are getting soggy.

137
00:17:48,818 --> 00:17:52,489
Let me see you.
Aw, honey, you got a spot.

138
00:18:01,331 --> 00:18:03,500
OK, here it comes.

139
00:18:05,543 --> 00:18:07,378
[screams]

140
00:18:16,805 --> 00:18:19,140
Something you were looking for, baby?

141
00:18:21,851 --> 00:18:23,686
Pop-Tarts?

142
00:18:25,814 --> 00:18:27,816
They're right here.

143
00:18:29,150 --> 00:18:30,819
Oh.

144
00:18:37,242 --> 00:18:39,494
What are you thinking, Mama?

145
00:18:41,371 --> 00:18:43,373
Lots of things.

146
00:18:44,874 --> 00:18:46,876
Anything bad about me?

147
00:18:46,918 --> 00:18:48,920
Hey, look at my face.

148
00:18:50,046 --> 00:18:52,882
I was not thinking
something bad about you.

149
00:18:54,050 --> 00:18:55,885
Got it?

150
00:18:58,138 --> 00:18:59,973
Got it.

151
00:19:01,432 --> 00:19:03,393
- Get up.
- [bell rings]

152
00:19:03,434 --> 00:19:05,895
- Th... that's Tommy, Mom.
- OK, you tuck it in.

153
00:19:05,979 --> 00:19:08,481
Hey, Cole? You want this?

154
00:19:38,636 --> 00:19:42,182
Hey, freak, how'd you like that
arm-around-the-shoulder bit?

155
00:19:42,265 --> 00:19:46,227
I just made that up. I went
with it as great actors do.

156
00:19:46,269 --> 00:19:48,271
It's called "improv".

157
00:19:53,359 --> 00:19:55,361
[bell ringing]

158
00:20:26,309 --> 00:20:28,144
Hey, baby.

159
00:20:29,145 --> 00:20:30,980
How was your day?

160
00:20:32,649 --> 00:20:34,317
Hmm?

161
00:20:38,071 --> 00:20:40,907
You know, you can
tell me things if you need to.

162
00:20:45,954 --> 00:20:48,957
Oh, you know what I did today?

163
00:20:48,998 --> 00:20:53,670
I, uh... I won the Pennsylvania
Lottery in the morning.

164
00:20:54,587 --> 00:20:56,506
I quit my jobs.

165
00:20:56,589 --> 00:20:59,509
And I ate a big picnic in the park

166
00:20:59,550 --> 00:21:01,344
with lots of chocolate mousse pie.

167
00:21:01,386 --> 00:21:05,014
And then I swam
in the fountain all afternoon.

168
00:21:05,056 --> 00:21:07,058
What'd you do?

169
00:21:12,105 --> 00:21:15,525
I was picked first for
kickball teams at recess.

170
00:21:15,608 --> 00:21:17,944
I hit a grand slam to win the game.

171
00:21:18,027 --> 00:21:21,864
Everybody lifted me up
and carried me around, cheering.

172
00:21:26,619 --> 00:21:29,998
In that case, I am gonna
make you some triangle pancakes.

173
00:21:30,873 --> 00:21:32,208
You got an hour.

174
00:21:38,464 --> 00:21:40,133
Hi.

175
00:21:45,054 --> 00:21:47,473
Want to sit?

176
00:21:51,686 --> 00:21:53,855
Don't feel like talking today?

177
00:21:58,026 --> 00:22:00,028
Wanna play a game?

178
00:22:01,404 --> 00:22:03,948
It's a mind-reading game.

179
00:22:04,032 --> 00:22:05,867
Here's how it works:

180
00:22:05,908 --> 00:22:08,244
I read your mind.

181
00:22:08,286 --> 00:22:11,914
If what I say is right, you
take one step towards the chair.

182
00:22:11,998 --> 00:22:14,083
If what I say is wrong,

183
00:22:14,125 --> 00:22:17,086
you take one step back
towards the doorway.

184
00:22:18,087 --> 00:22:21,382
If you reach the chair,
you sit down.

185
00:22:21,424 --> 00:22:24,677
If you reach the door, you can go.

186
00:22:26,846 --> 00:22:28,681
Wanna play?

187
00:22:36,647 --> 00:22:38,316
OK.

188
00:22:44,781 --> 00:22:46,783
[humming]

189
00:22:53,790 --> 00:22:57,168
When your mother and father
were first divorced,

190
00:22:57,251 --> 00:23:01,798
your mom went to see a doctor
like me, and he didn't help her,

191
00:23:02,715 --> 00:23:05,218
so you think I'm not
going to be able to help you.

192
00:23:20,775 --> 00:23:25,196
You're worried that
she said she told him things,

193
00:23:25,279 --> 00:23:27,782
things she couldn't tell anyone else.

194
00:23:29,283 --> 00:23:31,411
Secrets.

195
00:23:38,334 --> 00:23:40,878
You have a secret,
but you don't want to tell me.

196
00:23:54,183 --> 00:23:56,269
Your dad gave you
that watch as a present

197
00:23:56,352 --> 00:23:58,354
just before he went away.

198
00:24:09,198 --> 00:24:11,576
He forgot it in a drawer.

199
00:24:11,659 --> 00:24:13,661
Doesn't work.

200
00:24:25,381 --> 00:24:28,593
You keep pretty quiet
in school, but...

201
00:24:28,676 --> 00:24:30,678
...you're a good student.

202
00:24:30,720 --> 00:24:34,056
You've never really been
in any serious trouble.

203
00:24:41,022 --> 00:24:43,274
We were supposed
to draw a picture.

204
00:24:43,357 --> 00:24:45,359
Anything we wanted.

205
00:24:48,154 --> 00:24:50,740
I drew a man...

206
00:24:50,823 --> 00:24:54,494
...got hurt in the neck by
another man with a screwdriver.

207
00:24:57,830 --> 00:24:59,999
You saw that on TV, Cole?

208
00:25:04,378 --> 00:25:06,631
Everyone got upset.

209
00:25:07,673 --> 00:25:10,468
They had a meeting.

210
00:25:10,551 --> 00:25:12,678
Mom started crying.

211
00:25:12,762 --> 00:25:15,598
I don't draw like that anymore.

212
00:25:17,099 --> 00:25:19,519
How do you draw now?

213
00:25:21,354 --> 00:25:24,857
Draw... people smiling...

214
00:25:24,941 --> 00:25:26,943
...dogs running...

215
00:25:28,319 --> 00:25:30,154
...rainbows.

216
00:25:31,280 --> 00:25:33,950
They don't have
meetings about rainbows.

217
00:25:35,785 --> 00:25:37,620
No.

218
00:25:37,703 --> 00:25:39,747
I guess they don't.

219
00:25:47,838 --> 00:25:50,758
What am I thinking now?

220
00:25:50,800 --> 00:25:53,469
I don't know what you're thinking now.

221
00:26:00,726 --> 00:26:02,562
I was thinking,

222
00:26:02,645 --> 00:26:04,647
you're nice...

223
00:26:06,732 --> 00:26:09,235
...but you can't help me.

224
00:26:22,665 --> 00:26:24,417
[sighs]

225
00:26:24,917 --> 00:26:27,503
I thought you meant
the other Italian restaurant

226
00:26:27,587 --> 00:26:29,505
I asked you to marry me in.

227
00:26:34,010 --> 00:26:35,970
[sighs]

228
00:26:36,012 --> 00:26:38,014
I'm so sorry, Anna.

229
00:26:39,390 --> 00:26:42,059
I just can't seem to keep track of time.

230
00:26:44,812 --> 00:26:47,815
And I didn't have
a very good session today. I...

231
00:26:50,526 --> 00:26:52,153
[sighs]

232
00:26:52,194 --> 00:26:55,072
They're both so similar.

233
00:26:55,156 --> 00:26:58,034
Same mannerisms,
same expressions, same...

234
00:26:58,075 --> 00:27:00,411
...things hanging over their head.

235
00:27:02,913 --> 00:27:05,249
I think it might be some kind of abuse.

236
00:27:06,584 --> 00:27:10,212
Cole has... scratches on his arm.

237
00:27:10,296 --> 00:27:12,673
I think they might be fingernail cuts.

238
00:27:12,715 --> 00:27:15,843
Defensive cuts, maybe.
I don't know, Anna.

239
00:27:15,885 --> 00:27:17,511
[sighs]

240
00:27:17,553 --> 00:27:19,889
Maybe a teacher or a neighbour.

241
00:27:19,972 --> 00:27:23,476
I don't think it's the mother.
I've seen her with him, and...

242
00:27:23,559 --> 00:27:25,561
...doesn't seem to fit.

243
00:27:28,147 --> 00:27:30,316
Or I could just be wrong.

244
00:27:30,399 --> 00:27:33,569
Maybe he's just a kid who
likes to climb trees a lot.

245
00:27:41,952 --> 00:27:44,121
[sighs] Anna...

246
00:27:45,498 --> 00:27:49,085
I know that I've been
a little distant. I...

247
00:27:49,126 --> 00:27:51,545
I know that it makes
you mad. I just...

248
00:27:51,587 --> 00:27:54,006
...feel like I'm being
given a second chance

249
00:27:54,090 --> 00:27:56,258
and I don't want it to slip away.

250
00:27:58,094 --> 00:27:59,929
Anna.

251
00:28:01,097 --> 00:28:03,099
Happy anniversary.

252
00:28:10,523 --> 00:28:12,608
[sighs]

253
00:28:12,692 --> 00:28:15,069
[Cole] Stop looking at me.

254
00:28:15,111 --> 00:28:17,905
I don't like when people
look at me like that.

255
00:28:17,947 --> 00:28:19,615
OK.

256
00:28:20,866 --> 00:28:24,286
I walk this way to school
with Tommy Tammisimo.

257
00:28:24,370 --> 00:28:26,372
He your best buddy?

258
00:28:26,455 --> 00:28:28,457
He hates me.

259
00:28:28,499 --> 00:28:30,960
Do you hate him?

260
00:28:31,001 --> 00:28:32,670
No.

261
00:28:34,588 --> 00:28:36,841
Did your mom set that up?

262
00:28:36,924 --> 00:28:38,592
Yes.

263
00:28:40,511 --> 00:28:43,556
Did you ever talk to your mom
about how things are with Tommy?

264
00:28:43,639 --> 00:28:45,891
- I don't tell her things.
- Why not?

265
00:28:45,975 --> 00:28:49,019
She doesn't look at me like
everybody else. I don't want her to.

266
00:28:49,103 --> 00:28:51,981
- I don't want her to know.
